      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, parameter packs are a little confusing the first time you see them.  It basically says, pass the number of vectors equal to the number of arguments to op(), at least one.\n\nUnary Ops just takes Vec\u003cN,T\u003e x, and Ys... is a pack of zero other types.\n\nBinary Ops take Vec\u003cN,T\u003e x, and Ys... expands to the single other argument type---in all cases here also Vec\u003cN,T\u003e, but there\u0027s no way to say \"I take any number of a given type\" in C++.  It\u0027s got to be \"I take any number of any type\" that gets constrained somehow otherwise.\n\nIf we had three argument operations, they\u0027d take a vector x, and Ys... would expand to the other two arguments in order.\n\nys[0]... similiarly expands to nothing for unary Ops, to something like `y[0]` for binary, something like `y[0], z[0]` for ternary, etc.\nys.vals... expands to nothing for unary ops, `y.vals` for binary Ops, to `y.vals, z.vals` for ternary, etc.\n\nBut seeing as std::transform() doesn\u0027t actually support anything other than unary or binary ops, now that I\u0027ve said all that, I\u0027ve just rewritten map() to have two separate versions, one for unary and one for binary Ops.  This also lets me move the op back to the end of the parameter list, which is a little more familiar for this sort of thing.",
